Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Nghe An is a province in the North Central Coast region of Viet Nam and is Viet Nam's largest province by area.

The first flu case/death from H5N6 was noted in May 2015 in a 49-year-old man from China, Nanbu county, Sichuan province, who had been exposed to dead poultry and died in a hospital after receiving treatment. He suffered a severe case of pneumonia and avian influenza H5N6 strain was detected in a throat swab. This was considered an isolated case. People who had close contact with the patient did not show any symptoms after medical observation. It was thought that because of the widespread distribution of this virus and the rare human infection, that H5N6 is not easily transmissible between birds and humans.

Since early 2013, several new avian influenza virus strains have been reported in East and Southeast Asia, threatening both poultry-dependent livelihoods and human health. In March 2013, avian influenza A(H7N9) emerged in China causing a total of 456 human cases, and claiming 172 lives as of 5 Nov 2014 [645 cases as of 5 Apr 2015]. The virus is of low pathogenicity in poultry (no clinical signs are observed in infected birds, making control difficult) but can cause lethal pulmonary infection in mammals.

Sporadic human cases have also occurred from other avian influenza strains in China. In May 2013, a 20-year-old woman became the 1st human to be infected with another bird flu strain, H6N1. The woman had not been exposed to poultry and she recovered after a few days, according to Taiwanese health officials. In December 2013, China reported the 1st human case of avian flu virus, H10N8, in a 73-year-old woman from Jiangxi province. (http://www.cnn.com/2014/05/07/health/h5n6-flu-china-death/index.html ). 3 additional cases were reported, 2 of whom died.

"Low-path" H5N6 appears to circulate widely globally. But high-path avian influenza H5N6 is a '2nd-generation' HPAI H5 virus that has shown an ability to infect and seriously sicken humans. In early May 2014, the People's Democratic Republic reported outbreaks in poultry caused by highly pathogenic H5N6. This highly pathogenic virus has caused at least 7 H5N6 poultry outbreaks in Viet Nam with the initial outbreak in April 2014 following 2 outbreaks in Lao People's Democratic Republic. The viruses from these 2 countries have been shown to be genetically similar. In March 2015, the Xinhua News Agency reported an outbreak of H5N6 bird flu virus in poultry in Viet Nam's central Thanh Hoa province. According to a report by the Thanh Hoa provincial department of agriculture and rural development on 12 Mar 2015, a bird flu outbreak occurred in a farm in Hai Linh commune, leaving 293 birds sick. H5N6 bird flu virus in poultry was reported in Viet Nam's northern Lang Son and central Ha Tinh provinces in mid-August 2014, according to Viet Nam's Ministry of Health's General Department of Preventive Medicine. Outbreaks spread to several localities across the country including northern Lao Cai, Bac Giang, Phu Tho, central Quang Tri, Quang Ngai, Thua Thien Hue, and Quang Nam provinces. (http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/xinhua-news-agency/150318/h5n6-bird-flu-virus-poultry-reported-c-vietnam).

The diversity of avian influenza viral strains circulating in eastern Asia threatens to give rise to new reassortant viruses in addition to H5N6, with unpredictable consequences for animal and human health. H5N6 should be included among a growing list of emerging disease threats that demand attention through constant monitoring and maintenance of preparedness to respond.

For further reading on H5N6, go to Avian influenza A(H5N6): the latest addition to emerging zoonotic avian influenza threats in East and Southeast Asia. VOL 30 http://www.fao.org/3/a-i4199e.pdf
